Oh, I was only commenting on the use of the variable to store and label a condition.<p>For example, I prefer:<p><pre><code>  var insideEventTime = time > start && time < end;
  if (insideEventTime)
    ...
</code></pre>
To this:<p><pre><code>  // When inside event time
  if (time > start && time < end)
    ...
</code></pre>
I find comments frequently become inaccurate compared to function and variable names.

Any idea how this will end up working in practice? If it will actually <i>require</i> linking to an external .wasm file, that&#x27;ll break the way we&#x27;re currently using asm.js.<p>I&#x27;d like to see something that works more or less to the effect of:<p><pre><code>    const wasmCode = new Uint8Array(...);

    if (typeof executeWasm !== &#x27;undefined&#x27;) {
        executeWasm(wasmCode);
    }
    else {
        compileToAsmjs(wasmCode);
    }</code></pre>
